################################################################################
# UNION MERGING

# Files for human consumption that have an "append-only" behavior (where the
# changes are always additions to the place in the file), such as change logs,
# will often have merge conflicts and those merge conflicts are usually
# resolved by accepting both their and our changes. This can be handled
# automatically using the "union" merge driver:
#
# > union
# >
# > Run 3-way file level merge for text files, but take lines from both
# > versions, instead of leaving conflict markers. This tends to leave the
# > added lines in the resulting file in random order and the user should
# > verify the result. Do not use this if you do not understand the
# > implications.
#
# As stated in that description, we MUST check the files after a merge to
# ensure that the merge happened as expected.
#
# See: https://git-scm.com/docs/gitattributes#_built_in_merge_drivers

CHANGELOG* merge=union

################################################################################
# GIT-LFS

# All binary files should be stored using git's Large File Storage technique,
# which is much more efficient than tracking the entire content of each binary
# file directly in the git repo.
#
# See:
# - https://git-lfs.com/

